        "theme":  "Strategy",
        "summary":  "An IBM Institute for Business Value study found that more than 70% of senior executives report difficulty switching from their primary AI provider, while 68% cite data residency and sovereignty requirements as obstacles to relocating AI systems. The research positions AI sovereignty ΓÇö the ability to maintain control over AI infrastructure and data ΓÇö as an emerging enterprise priority as AI adoption accelerates. IBM uses the findings to frame vendor independence and open architectures as essential risk-management considerations.",
        "execSummary":  "Vendor lock-in, long a concern in cloud and SaaS, is now the dominant anxiety in enterprise AI infrastructure decisions. IBM\u0027s research quantifies the problem: more than seven in ten executives already feel trapped with their primary AI provider, and data sovereignty rules make migration even harder. For enterprise and customer-support leaders making platform commitments now, this data argues for prioritizing interoperability, open standards, and contract exit rights before signing long-term AI deals. The caveat is that this research originates from IBM, which has a direct commercial interest in positioning its own open-architecture offerings as the antidote.",
