        "date":  "2026-06-26",
        "theme":  "Agents",
        "summary":  "A Kyndryl survey of 1,100 business leaders found that only 25% fully trust their AI systems, yet over 80% of technology leaders expect autonomous AI agents to make consequential business decisions within the year. Two-thirds of respondents have already granted AI agents read-write access to core infrastructure, advancing autonomy faster than trust has developed. Organizations are responding primarily by redesigning employee roles and investing in workforce upskilling rather than external hiring.",
        "execSummary":  "Enterprises are deploying autonomous AI agents at a pace that significantly outstrips the trust and governance maturity needed to manage them safely ΓÇö a gap that carries material operational risk. The Kyndryl data is striking: most organizations have already granted agents write access to critical systems even though three-quarters of leaders do not fully trust those systems. For customer-support and operations leaders, this is a direct warning: agentic systems making consequential decisions without sufficient human oversight create liability and service-failure risks that are difficult to contain after the fact. The watch item is workforce redesign ΓÇö organizations that treat this purely as a technology deployment rather than a role-redesign initiative are likely to see both trust deficits and adoption failures.",
